Yes, absolutely. Hybrid Search is fundamentally the combination of Dense and Sparse Retrieval. They are two sides of the same coin.

Here is the direct mapping of the terms you asked about:

Concept in Previous Explanation Technical Term Why that Name?
Keyword Search (BM25) Sparse Retrieval The vector representing the text is mostly zeros (sparse). Only words present in the document get a non-zero value.
Vector Search (Embeddings) Dense Retrieval The vector is a list of 384/768/1536 numbers where every single dimension has a value (dense).

The Relationship Explained

1. Sparse Retrieval (The "Exact Match" Specialist)

· Mechanism: Uses TF-IDF or BM25 algorithms.
· Vector Nature: Imagine a dictionary of 50,000 words. A document gets a vector of length 50,000. Only the words "Project," "X," and "21" have a value of 1.2; the other 49,997 slots are 0. This is Sparse.
· Relation to Hybrid: This is the Keyword leg of Hybrid Search.

2. Dense Retrieval (The "Meaning" Specialist)

· Mechanism: Uses Embedding Models (like text-embedding-3-small or bge-m3).
· Vector Nature: A document is compressed into a small array like [0.012, -0.345, 0.887, ...]. Every single number in that array is non-zero. This is Dense.
· Relation to Hybrid: This is the Semantic leg of Hybrid Search.

Why We Use Both (The Technical Reason)

You asked: "Has it anything to do with dense or sparse?"

Yes. It is the only way to solve the vocabulary mismatch problem.

· Sparse retrieves based on lexical intersection (shared words).
· Dense retrieves based on neural similarity (shared concepts).

Hybrid Search strategies (like RRF) are simply the fusion algorithms we use to combine the Sparse Result List and the Dense Result List into one final, superior list.

In summary: Hybrid Search is Sparse + Dense Retrieval. You cannot implement Hybrid Search without using both a Sparse Index (like Elasticsearch/Lucene) and a Dense Vector Database (like Pinecone/Qdrant/PGVector)
